---

<DocsLayout title="Tenants & Users">
  <h1>Tenants &amp; Users</h1>
  <p>EntDB separates <strong>cross-tenant identity</strong> (users, tenants, memberships) from <strong>per-tenant data</strong> (nodes, edges, ACLs). The cross-tenant state lives in a single <code>global.db</code> SQLite file managed by <code>GlobalStore</code>; every tenant otherwise gets its own isolated SQLite database. Admin RPCs on the gRPC service let you bootstrap and manage that global state from the SDK.</p>

  <h2>The Identity Model</h2>
  <p>There are three concepts to keep straight:</p>
  <table>
    <tr><th>Concept</th><th>Where it lives</th><th>Identifier shape</th></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>User</strong></td><td><code>user_registry</code> in <code>global.db</code></td><td><code>"alice"</code> (raw <code>user_id</code>)</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Tenant</strong></td><td><code>tenant_registry</code> in <code>global.db</code></td><td><code>"acme"</code> (raw <code>tenant_id</code>)</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Membership</strong></td><td><code>tenant_members</code> in <code>global.db</code></td><td><code>(tenant_id, user_id, role)</code></td></tr>
  </table>
  <p>A user can belong to many tenants with a different role in each. Tenants have no implicit membership: a user has zero access to a tenant until <code>add_tenant_member</code> creates a row.</p>

  <h2>user_id vs tenant_principal</h2>
  <p>The same person is identified two different ways depending on which boundary you are on:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong><code>user_id</code></strong> — the bare identifier (<code>"alice"</code>) used by the global registry, the <code>tenant_members</code> table, GDPR APIs, and admin RPCs.</li>
    <li><strong><code>tenant_principal</code> / actor</strong> — the same identity prefixed for use inside a tenant's ACL system (<code>"user:alice"</code> for users, <code>"group:eng"</code> for groups, <code>"system:admin"</code> for the platform).</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Translation happens at the gRPC boundary. The auth interceptor publishes a verified identity into a context-var; <code>get_authoritative_actor</code> normalizes it to a <code>user:&lt;id&gt;</code> actor before any ACL check runs. That means client code passes <code>user_id="alice"</code> to admin APIs and <code>actor="user:alice"</code> to data APIs &mdash; never mixed.</p>

  <h2>Creating Tenants</h2>
  <p><code>create_tenant</code> registers a new tenant in the global registry. It is idempotent only on the SDK return shape (an existing <code>tenant_id</code> raises an error from the underlying <code>INSERT</code>). The new tenant has no members yet.</p>
  <CodeTabs
    python={`async with DbClient("localhost:50051", api_key="eks_...") as db:
    result = await db.create_tenant(
        tenant_id="acme",
        name="Acme Corp",
        actor="system:admin",
    )
    # result == {"success": True, "tenant": {...}, "error": ""}`}
    go={`tenant, err := client.Admin().CreateTenant(
    ctx, "system:admin", "acme", "Acme Corp",
)
// tenant.TenantID == "acme", tenant.Status == "active"`}
  />

  <h2>Creating Users</h2>
  <p>Users are created independently of any tenant. The <code>email</code> field is unique across the entire registry; reusing it raises <code>sqlite3.IntegrityError</code> on the server.</p>
  <CodeTabs
    python={`await db.create_user(
    user_id="alice",
    email="alice@acme.test",
    name="Alice Anderson",
    actor="system:admin",
)
# {"success": True, "user": {"user_id": "alice", ...}}`}
    go={`user, err := client.Admin().CreateUser(
    ctx, "system:admin",
    "alice", "alice@acme.test", "Alice Anderson",
)
// user.UserID == "alice", user.Status == "active"`}
  />

  <h2>Memberships and Roles</h2>
  <p>A membership row binds a user to a tenant with a role string. The server treats roles as opaque strings; the canonical values are:</p>
  <table>
    <tr><th>Role</th><th>Meaning</th></tr>
    <tr><td><code>owner</code></td><td>Full administrative control, including transferring tenant ownership and removing other admins.</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>admin</code></td><td>Manage members, run admin operations (transfer, revoke, delegate), but cannot remove an <code>owner</code>.</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>member</code></td><td>Default role. Can create and own nodes; subject to ACL on everything else.</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>viewer</code></td><td>Read-only convention; not a hard server enforcement &mdash; ACL grants are still the source of truth on individual nodes.</td></tr>
  </table>

  <h3>Adding members</h3>
  <CodeTabs
    python={`await db.add_tenant_member(
    tenant_id="acme",
    user_id="alice",
    role="member",
    actor="system:admin",
)`}
    go={`err := client.Admin().AddTenantMember(
    ctx, "system:admin", "acme", "alice", "member",
)`}
  />

  <h3>Promoting or changing a role</h3>
  <CodeTabs
    python={`await db.change_member_role(
    tenant_id="acme",
    user_id="alice",
    new_role="admin",
    actor="system:admin",
)`}
    go={`err := client.Admin().ChangeMemberRole(
    ctx, "system:admin", "acme", "alice", "admin",
)`}
  />

  <h3>Removing a member</h3>
  <p>Removing a membership only deletes the row from <code>tenant_members</code>. It does <strong>not</strong> reassign nodes the user owns or revoke their direct ACL grants &mdash; for that, see <a href="/tenant-shard-db/docs/admin/operations">Admin Operations</a> (<code>transfer_user_content</code> and <code>revoke_all_user_access</code>).</p>
  <CodeTabs
    python={`await db.remove_tenant_member(
    tenant_id="acme",
    user_id="alice",
    actor="system:admin",
)`}
    go={`err := client.Admin().RemoveTenantMember(
    ctx, "system:admin", "acme", "alice",
)`}
  />

  <h2>Listing Memberships</h2>
  <p>Two symmetric reads: members of a tenant, or tenants of a user.</p>
  <CodeTabs
    python={`# Everyone in a tenant
members = await db.get_tenant_members("acme", actor="system:admin")
# [{"tenant_id": "acme", "user_id": "alice", "role": "admin", "joined_at": ...}, ...]

# Everywhere a user belongs
tenancies = await db.get_user_tenants("alice", actor="system:admin")
# [{"tenant_id": "acme", "user_id": "alice", "role": "admin", ...}, ...]`}
    go={`// Everyone in a tenant
members, err := client.Admin().GetTenantMembers(ctx, "system:admin", "acme")
// []entdb.TenantMember{{TenantID: "acme", UserID: "alice", Role: "admin", JoinedAt: ...}, ...}

// Everywhere a user belongs
tenancies, err := client.Admin().GetUserTenants(ctx, "system:admin", "alice")`}
  />

  <h2>End-to-end: bootstrap a tenant</h2>
  <p>A complete flow: create the tenant, create a user, invite them, promote them, then remove them.</p>
  <CodeTabs
    python={`async with DbClient("localhost:50051", api_key="eks_...") as db:
    await db.create_tenant("acme", "Acme Corp")
    await db.create_user("alice", "alice@acme.test", "Alice")

    # 1. Invite as a regular member
    await db.add_tenant_member("acme", "alice", role="member")

    # 2. Promote to admin
    await db.change_member_role("acme", "alice", new_role="admin")

    # 3. Off-board: revoke ACL grants, then drop the membership
    await db.revoke_all_user_access("acme", "alice")
    await db.remove_tenant_member("acme", "alice")`}
    go={`admin := client.Admin()
const root = "system:admin"

if _, err := admin.CreateTenant(ctx, root, "acme", "Acme Corp"); err != nil {
    return err
}
if _, err := admin.CreateUser(ctx, root, "alice", "alice@acme.test", "Alice"); err != nil {
    return err
}

// 1. Invite as a regular member
if err := admin.AddTenantMember(ctx, root, "acme", "alice", "member"); err != nil {
    return err
}

// 2. Promote to admin
if err := admin.ChangeMemberRole(ctx, root, "acme", "alice", "admin"); err != nil {
    return err
}

// 3. Off-board: revoke ACL grants, then drop the membership
if _, err := admin.RevokeAllUserAccess(ctx, root, "acme", "alice"); err != nil {
    return err
}
if err := admin.RemoveTenantMember(ctx, root, "acme", "alice"); err != nil {
    return err
}`}
  />

  <h2>Where the data lives</h2>
  <p>If you need to inspect or back up the cross-tenant state directly, the relevant tables in <code>{`{data_dir}/global.db`}</code> are <code>user_registry</code>, <code>tenant_registry</code>, and <code>tenant_members</code>. Per-tenant payloads, ACLs, and edges live in <code>{`{data_dir}/tenants/{tenant_id}.db`}</code> and are never read across tenant boundaries in a single SQLite transaction.</p>

